flowRoot.flowPara: The aim of this page is to develop a consistent set of rules for presenting menus. In practical terms this generally means containing the menu inside a popover.
Menus have consistent styling - the same background color, spacing, corner radius. If the menu is in reference to a square or round shape, it points at it.

Pluto was discovered by Clyde Tombaugh in 1930 and was originally considered to be the ninth planet from the Sun. After 1992, its status as a planet was questioned following the discovery of several objects of similar size in the Kuiper belt.
Standard icon button menu. The button is square and compact so the menu has a point.
Context menu. The target is square so the menu has a point.
The same context menu as the grid example. Because it's a list row, it's not always clear where the menu should point, so there's no point.
Same rule for the point as with the list view example.
This isn't a menu, but it's a popover and its opened from a button. The aim is to have styling which feels consistent, but also communicates that it's not really a menu.

This isn't a menu, although it is very similar to one. The only difference is that a menu would use radio buttons. There is precedence for using check marks elsewhere in GNOME, so either approach is viable.
